    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moths Have an Even, Too</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <dateline>SYDNEY, Australia, Sept. 25</dateline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Hundreds of moths descend on Sydney, apparently attracted by lights from Olympic Games (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>As television cameras high above Olympic Stadium pull back to reveal the magnificent panorama below, the first thing a viewer notices may be the moths. Hundreds of thousands of them, jammed almost wing to wing around the stadium lights, appear on television like shimmering stars.</p>
        <p>They are Bogong moths, distracted from their southward migration through New South Wales to the Bogong region of Alpine National Park in northern Victoria.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>As television cameras high above Olympic Stadium pull back to reveal the magnificent panorama below, the first thing a viewer notices may be the moths. Hundreds of thousands of them, jammed almost wing to wing around the stadium lights, appear on television like shimmering stars.</p>
        <p>They are Bogong moths, distracted from their southward migration through New South Wales to the Bogong region of Alpine National Park in northern Victoria.</p>
        <p>Sydney's Olympic organizers consider the moths pests, and they find it necessary to announce at night baseball games that the huge moths are harmless. The lights at Olympic Stadium are an even bigger temptation, and stadium managers will dim the field lights and turn off the external stadium lights at midnight rather than at 3 a.m. to encourage the moths' departure. Jayne Pearce, a spokeswoman for the track and field events, said no athletes had complained, but that the cleaning staff has been instructed to pay special attention to moth carcasses.</p>
        <p>SYDNEY 2000</p>
      </block>
